olars, not to mention by lawmakers, as too difficult to answer.This collection of essays helps us understand some of the dimensions of these questions by seeing how various disciplines have dealt with them. A developmental psychologist examines the contribution her discipline can make to the topic. A historian explores the origins of the present penal system. An anthropologist places sanctions and rewards in the context of past and present societies. An economist measures the potential effectiveness of deterence. Other experts in law, political science, organizational behaviour, and sociology offer unique perspectives.This book is the first stage in a program on sanctions and rewards in the legal system sponsored by the Canadian Institute for Advanced Research and part of the Institute's wider program on law and society.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aReward (Law)vCongresses. 0aSanctions (Law)vCongresses. 7aLAW / Legal Profession.2bisacsh1 aArnold, Hugh J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBeattie, John M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCook, Philip J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriedland, Martin, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aGrusec, Joan E., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLaurence Ross, H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMaranda, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRabin, Robert L., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aStone, Christopher D., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTuohy, Carolyn, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aZimring, Franklin E., econtrib